{{en-noun}}
# {{lb|en|literary|derogatory|dated}} An [[ill-tempered]] [[woman]].
#: {{synonyms|en|Thesaurus:shrew}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Taming of the Shrew|act=I|scene=ii|page=213|column=1|passage=Be ſhe as foule as was ''Florentius'' Loue, / As old as ''[[Sybil|Sibell]]'', and as curſt and [[shrewd|ſhrow'd]] / As ''Socrates '''Zentippe''''', or a worſe: / She moues me not, or not remoues at leaſt / Affections edge in me.|brackets=on}}
#* {{RQ:Wood Athenae Oxonienses|volume=I|entry=RICHARD HOOKER|column=262|passage=[[w:Richard Hooker|RICHARD HOOKER]], that rare and admirable Theologiſt, [...] married a clowniſh ſilly Woman and withal a meer '''''Xantippe''''', [...]}}
#* {{RQ:Fielding Tom Jones|volume=III|book=VIII|chapter=In which the Man of the Hill Begins to Relate His History|pages=235–236|pageref=236|passage=&#91;[https://books.google.com/books?id=4J9aAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA235 page 235]&#93; He was prudent and induſtrious, and ſo good a Huſbandman, that he might have led a very eaſy and comfortable Life, had not an errant Vixen of a Wife ſoured his domeſtic Quiet. [...] &#91;[https://books.google.com/books?id=4J9aAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA236 page 236]&#93; By this '''''Xantippe''''' (ſo was the Wife of ''Socrates'' called, ſaid ''Partridge'') By this '''''Xantippe''''' he had two Sons, of which I was the younger.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=W. C. Goldthwait|title=Power of Expression|editor=W. W. Mitchell|magazine=The Massachusetts Teacher|location=Boston, Mass.|publisher=Samuel Coolidge,{{nb...|No. 16 Devonshire Street.}}|month=September|year=1850|volume=III|issue=9|page=286|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=7dwBAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA286|issn=2642-6536|oclc=7516213|passage=Who has not seen the cross looks and peevish temper of the teacher and parent copied, as by a mirror (though we should say without ''reflection''), in the face and disposition of the child? [...] From an unbroken course of such treatment, who would expect any thing but an unbroken line of {{w|Nabal}}s and '''Xanthippes'''?}}
#* {{RQ:Trollope Doctor Thorne|volume=II|chapter=Louis Scatcherd|pages=185–186|pageref=185|passage=What have we seen in our own personal walks through life to make us believe that women are devils? There may possibly have been a '''Xantippe''' here and there, but [[w:Imogen (Cymbeline)|Imogenes]] are to be found under every bush.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|title=Socrates. Part I.|magazine=[[w:Dublin University Magazine|Dublin University Magazine, a Literary and Political Journal]]|location=Dublin|publisher=George Herbert,{{nb...|117, Grafton-Street}}; London: [[w:Hurst and Blackett|Hurst & Blackett]]|month=July|year=1870|volume=LXXVI|issue=CCCCLI|page=114|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=WGIZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA114|column=1|oclc=828212439|passage=The ''use'' he &#91;{{w|Socrates}}&#93; made of his domestic trial may be profitably remembered by any that have a '''Xanthippe''' to deal with.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Arthur H[enderson] Smith|authorlink=Arthur Henderson Smith|title=The Proverbs and Common Sayings of the Chinese. [...] Puns and Other Linguistic Diversion.—Parodies.|magazine=[[w:Chinese Recorder and Missionary Journal|The Chinese Recorder and Missionary Journal]]|location=Shanghai|publisher=[[w:Presbyterian Mission Agency|American Presbyterian Mission Press]]|month=January–February|year=1884|volume=XV|issue=1|section=footnote *|page=14|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=aMwWAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA14|oclc=6781272|passage=The 'kneeling punishment' ({{lang|zh|罰跪}}) would seem to be a well recognized mode of enforcing their authority, in use by Chinese '''Xanthippes''', for the proverb says: 'The Henpecked man is obliged to kneel with a lamp on his head [to make it certain that he does not stir] until the morning watch.'}}
